definition.value: A nucleotide is a nucleoside phosphate resulting from the condensation of the 3 or 5 hydroxy group of a nucleoside with phosphoric acid.
An organoiodine compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-iodine bond.
A polysaccharide composed of glucose residues.
Glycans composed of a single type of monosaccharide residue. They are named by replacing the ending '-ose' of the sugar by '-an'.
Polysaccharides composed of galactose residues.
Polysaccharides composed of xylose residues.
A trimethoxyflavone that is flavone substituted by methoxy groups at positions 6, 7 and 3' and hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 4' respectively.
Any ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a ring.
A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the pteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid units.
A benzoate ester that is any ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of gallic acid (3,4,5-trihydroxybenzoic acid) with an alcoholic or phenolic hydroxy group.
A molecular entity consisting of two or more chemical elements.
Any heteroatomic molecular entity that is a chemical compound of halogen with other chemical elements.
A lactone having a five-membered lactone ring.

LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, antimicrobial synergist, emulsifier, humectant, moisture-retention agent, stabilizer, sequestrant, texturizing agent.

LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, buffer, emulsifier, humectant, moisture-retention agent, raising agent, sequestrant, stabilizer, texturizing agent.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive.
An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.
A memeber of the class of anthocyanin chlorides that has cyanidin 3-O-beta-D-galactoside  as the cationic counterpart.
An aldohexose that is the C-2 epimer of glucose.
Any imide in which the acyl substituents are any two from carboacyl, sulfonyl and phosphoryl
A straight chain alkane composed of 4 carbon atoms.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): propellant.
A dye derived by condensation of phthalic anhydride with resorcinol (and derivatives) or m-aminophenol (and derivatives).
Any carbohydrate sulfate that is a polysaccharide carrying at least one O-sulfo substituent.
An aryl sulfate that is dopamine in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a sulfo group.
A spiro compound in which at least one of the cyclic components is an oxygen heterocyle.
The stable isotope of phosphorus with relative atomic mass 30.973762 and nuclear spin (1)/2.
The stable isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 31.972071. The most abundant (95.02 atom percent) isotope of naturally occurring sulfur.
A macromolecule derived from one species of (real, implicit or hypothetical) monomer.
A member of the class of anthocyanin chlorides that has cyanin cation as the cationic counterpart.
A compound composed of two or more pyrrole units.
Any organonitrogen compound containing a cyclic component with nitrogen and at least one other element as ring member atoms.
Any organic heterocyclic compound containing at least one ring oxygen atom.
